on its way to being the next major consumer tech platform. And yes, that ma=
y have been obvious =E2=80=94 those usage numbers don=E2=80=99t lie =E2=80=
=94 but I think this launch was meaningful for what it signaled about OpenA=
I=E2=80=99s acceptance of that reality=E2=80=A6

This takes me back to Marc Andreessen=E2=80=99s famous essay about Product-=
Market Fit ( https://pmarchive.com/guide_to_startups_part4.html ) :

I=E2=80=99ll assert that market is the most important factor in a startup=
=E2=80=99s success or failure. Why? In a great market =E2=80=94 a market wi=
th lots of real potential customers =E2=80=94 the market pulls product out =
of the startup.

As I noted above, the market didn=E2=80=99t so much pull ChatGPT out of Ope=
nAI as they pulled the ambition to be a consumer tech company out of a grou=
p of researchers=E2=80=A6when it comes to meaningful consumer tech companie=
s, the product is actually the most important. The key to consumer products=
 is efficient customer acquisition, which means word-of-mouth and/or networ=
k effects; ChatGPT doesn=E2=80=99t really have the latter (yes, it gets fee=
dback), but it has an astronomical amount of the former (and, for what it=
=E2=80=99s worth, playing around with Friedman=E2=80=99s compare tool defin=
itely leaves the impression that OpenAI currently has the best product). In=
deed, the product that ChatGPT=E2=80=99s emergence most reminds me of is Go=
ogle: it simply was better than anything else on the market, which meant it=
 didn=E2=80=99t matter that it came from a couple of university students (t=
he origin stories are not dissimilar!).

